9.4 — pH of buffer after adding KOH (6 marks)
0.0136 mol KX + 100 cm³ of 0.500 mol dm⁻³ HX. Then 3.00 × 10⁻⁴ mol KOH added. Ka = 1.41 × 10⁻⁵ mol dm⁻³. Answer to 2 d.p.

Mark scheme:

M1 Ka = [H⁺][X⁻] / [HX] → [H⁺] = Ka × [HX] / [X⁻]
M2 mol HX = 0.100 × 0.500 = 0.0500 mol
M3 mol HX after KOH = 0.0500 − 3.00 × 10⁻⁴ = 0.0497 mol
M4 mol KX after KOH = 0.0136 + 3.00 × 10⁻⁴ = 0.0139 mol
M5 [H⁺] = 1.41 × 10⁻⁵ × 0.0497 / 0.0139 = 5.04 × 10⁻⁵
M6 pH = −log₁₀(5.04 × 10⁻⁵) = 4.30 (2 d.p.)
TIP

If M3 and M4 are not attempted, max 2 marks. If M3/M4 attempted but 3 × 10⁻⁴ not used correctly, max 4 marks.

9.5 — Why does a buffer have constant pH when diluted? (1 mark)
Mark scheme: pH = −log(Ka × [HX] / [X⁻]). Since both [HX] and [X⁻] are diluted equally, the ratio remains (almost) constant, so pH is unchanged.

